module IfPredDrop

(* The soundness sentinel for V2.4c step 2 — the analog of 25_minimum_redef.lark.

   A guarded predicate is admitted ONLY when all three of c, p, q translate.  Here
   the else branch is `v == x * x * x`, and `x * x * x` is NON-LINEAR — the ordinary
   way out of the fragment.  So `q` is untranslatable, the whole `if`-predicate is
   None, and the STRICT `formula()` at the declaration site rejects the contract.

   This file must stay REJECTED even AFTER step 2 lands.  If the new `IfExpr` case
   ever `or Top()`-ed an untranslatable branch — the shape of false proofs #2 and
   #7 — this contract would be silently admitted with a `true` where the source said
   `v == x * x * x`, and `f` could then claim anything on its negative inputs.  The
   rule is the one V1' installed for the solver and `_branch` installed for a
   program-position `if`: where the checker cannot translate, it says NOTHING.

   Expected: rejected at the declaration ("not a predicate in the decidable
   fragment: if ..."), never proved. *)

fn f(x : Int) : {v : Int | if x >= 0 then v == x else v == x * x * x} =
  x

fn main(io : IO) : IO =
  print(io, show(f(3)))
